Between Subjects¶

In [5]:
def plot_between_subjects(group_l=['CG', 'EG'], sheet_l=['alpha'], 
                          feat_l=['ratio_power_threshold'], 
                          protocol='eo', select_subjects=False, exclude_subjects=True,
                          save=False, plot_stats=True, stats_test='ttest_pair', 
                          scale=10, stats_loc=0.3, group_sufix='allsubjects'):
    #group to plot
    group_l=group_l # ["CG", "EG"], ["CG"], ["EG"]
    #protocol to plot
    protocol=protocol
    #sheets to plot
    sheet_l=sheet_l #['alpha']-one band or ['theta','alpha','SMR','beta']-multiple band
    sheet_df_d={} #sheet df dict
    for sheet in sheet_l:
        sheet_df_d[sheet] = pd.read_excel(database_path, sheet_name=sheet)
        #select subjects - using 'eeg_alpha_groups'
        sheet_df=sheet_df_d[sheet]
        select_subjects=select_subjects
        group_sufix=group_sufix#default
        if select_subjects and not group_sufix=='allsubjects':
            group_sufix=group_sufix
            group=protocol+'_'+group_sufix #group of subjects
            subjects_l=eeg_alpha_groups['subject'].loc[(eeg_alpha_groups[group]==1)].tolist() #select subjects to list
            sheet_df=sheet_df.loc[sheet_df['subject'].isin(subjects_l)] #get alpha features dataframe of subjects
        exclude_subjects=exclude_subjects
        if exclude_subjects:
            group=protocol+'_EX_SUB' #group of subjects
            subjects_l=eeg_alpha_groups['subject'].loc[(eeg_alpha_groups[group]==1)].tolist() #select subjects to list
            sheet_df=sheet_df.loc[sheet_df['subject'].isin(subjects_l) != True]    #print([alpha_df['subject'].isin(subjects_l) != True])
        sheet_df_d[sheet]=sheet_df #substitute sheet_df
    #feature to plot
    feat_l=feat_l #'ratio_power_threshold', 'tBAT', 'tonic_increase', 'tonic_increase_BAT'
    #tasks to plot- [("x axis name","tasks to use")]
    task_l=[]
    if protocol=="eo":
        #task_l=[("BAS_0",['rest_eo_2']), ("NFT_1",['alpha_eo_3']), ("NFT_2",['alpha_eo_5','alpha_eo_7']), ("NFT_3",['alpha_eo_9','alpha_eo_11']), ("NFT_4",['alpha_eo_14'])]
        task_l=[("BAS_0",['rest_eo_2']), ("NFT_1",['alpha_eo_3']), ("PRIME_1", ["rest_eo_4", "breathingv6_eo_4","imageryv6_eo_4", "rest_eo_6", "breathingv6_eo_6","imageryv6_eo_6"]), ("NFT_2",['alpha_eo_5','alpha_eo_7']), ("PRIME_2", ["rest_eo_8", "breathingv6_eo_8","imageryv6_eo_8", "rest_eo_10", "breathingv6_eo_10","imageryv6_eo_10"]),("NFT_3",['alpha_eo_9','alpha_eo_11']), ("NFT_4",['alpha_eo_14'])]
    if protocol=="ec":
        #task_l=[("BAS_0",['rest_ec_1']), ("NFT_1",['alpha_ec_5','alpha_ec_7']), ("NFT_2",['alpha_eo_9','alpha_eo_11'])]
        task_l=[("BAS_0",['rest_ec_1']), ("PRIME_1", ["rest_ec_4", "breathingv6_ec_4","imageryv6_ec_4", "rest_ec_6", "breathingv6_ec_6","imageryv6_ec_6"]), ("NFT_1",['alpha_ec_5','alpha_ec_7']),  ("PRIME_2", ["rest_ec_8", "breathingv6_ec_8","imageryv6_ec_8", "rest_ec_10", "breathingv6_ec_10","imageryv6_ec_10"]), ("NFT_2",['alpha_ec_9','alpha_ec_11'])]


    #SAVE - file_sufix to add to filename and plot
    file_sufix=protocol+'_'+feat_l[0]+'_'+group_sufix
    save=save

    #PLOT STATs
    plot_stats=plot_stats
    task_ref_stats=task_l[0][0]#reference task to make stats
    #1) one-sample paired ttest: 1_measurement_var=tBAT, 1_nominal_var=subjects, 2_nominal_var=task_out-task_ref ; hipotheses: ; 
    # biological question: Whether the measurment var has gone up or down between task_out and task_ref.
    #null hypothesis: mean difference between paired observations is zero.
    #2) two-sample ttest (independent or dependent samples): 1_measurement_var=tBAT, 1_nominal_var=Task=['Task_out' vs 'Task_ref'];
    #assumption: normally distibuted; null hypothesis:  means of the measurement var are equal for the two categories.
    #http://www.biostathandbook.com/pairedttest.html
    stats_test=stats_test#"ttest_pair"; 'ttest_ind' , 'ttest_rel'
    scale=scale
    stats_loc=stats_loc#localization of stats
    e2_f.plot_group(datadir, save=save,group_l=group_l,task_l=task_l, sheet_l=sheet_l, sheet_df_d=sheet_df_d, feat_l=feat_l, file_sufix=file_sufix, uplims=True, lolims=True, plot_stats=plot_stats, task_ref_stats=task_ref_stats,stats_test=stats_test,stats_loc=stats_loc, scale=scale)
    return sheet_df_d, task_l

#Chose data to compare
data_1=np.array(CG_task_d['NFT_4'])
data_1=data_1[np.logical_not(np.isnan(data_1))] #REMOVE NaN
data_2=np.array(EG_task_d['NFT_4'])
data_2=data_2[np.logical_not(np.isnan(data_2))] #REMOVE NaN
print(len(data_1))
print(len(data_2))
#T-test Independent groups
stat, p = scipy.stats.ttest_ind(data_1, data_2, axis=0, equal_var=True, nan_policy='omit')
print('ttest_statistics=%.4f, p=%.4f' % (stat, p))

31
30
ttest_statistics=-0.5914, p=0.5565

Feature: Ratio task asolute power/ threshold absolute power(BAS_0)

p: p-value of paired t-test

var: variance is a measure of the spread of a distribution - average degree to which each point differs from the mean.

Feature changes:

  • R: overral feature increase => D: alpha power epoch distribution increases
  • R: EG and CG feature increase not different => D: Single-session can't descriminate power from priming vs no-priming

Stastical feature changes:

  • R: overral p-value decrease => D: alpha power epoch distribution increases significantly, therefore this training up-regulates alpha.
  • R: overral variability maintains => D: If an alpha self-regulation is represented by affecting the (lowering) variability, then this single-session training design can't answer that.
  • R: EG changes in variability superior to CG changes => D: Priming affects alpha power comparativily to CG.
  • R: CG less variability and more constant => D: REST No-priming intervention affects less the alpha amplitude

Highlights:

  • D: Does priming with external stimulation affects the self-regulation of NF?
    • D: Priming with external MM affects alpha NFT variability comparing to REST no-priming. Therefore, possibily can affect non-responders?

#Chose data to compare
data_1=np.array(CG_task_d['NFT_4'])
data_1=data_1[np.logical_not(np.isnan(data_1))] #REMOVE NaN
data_2=np.array(EG_task_d['NFT_4'])
data_2=data_2[np.logical_not(np.isnan(data_2))] #REMOVE NaN
print(len(data_1))
print(len(data_2))
#T-test Independent groups
stat, p = scipy.stats.ttest_ind(data_1, data_2, axis=0, equal_var=True, nan_policy='omit')
print('ttest_statistics=%.4f, p=%.4f' % (stat, p))

31
30
ttest_statistics=-1.1142, p=0.2697

Feature: tBAT (number of epochs above threshold / total number of epochs)

Feature changes:

  • R: overral feature increase => D: More epochs above threshold
  • R: EG and CG feature increase not different => D: Single-session can't descriminate power from priming vs no-priming

Stastical feature changes:

  • R: overral p-value decrease => D: number of epochs above threshold increase significantly
  • R: overral variability maintains => D: Ideally(see NFT_+) if all subjects increase the number of epochs above the threshold the distribution variance should decrease, however it seems that a similar distribution is maintained in a single-session design. Therefore, the number of responders and non-reponders should be the same between blocks.
  • R: EG p-value has a more sinificant decrease <0.001 => D: Alpha epochs above the threshold are affected wih more significance, comparing with the no-priming intervention.
  • R: EG p-value are constantly decreasing, while CG p-value is changing abruptly => D: The alpha epochs above threshold are constantly increasing in the EG population, therefore the priming seems to assist the alpha regulation, maintaining a similar alpha distribution.

Highlights:

  • R: Are MM stimuli a good self-regulation primer, compared with the standard rest baseline tasks used in Neurofeedback? Does priming with external stimulation assists participants in self-regulate their Neurofeedback?
    • MM stimuli seems to assist alpha regulation increasing constantly the number of epochs above threshold, comparing with the REST no-priming that seems to randomly assist the epochs above threshold.
